<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,1627,1797]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<taxonomicName box="[151,418,1627,1653]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Colobaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigroaristata">
<emphasis box="[151,418,1627,1653]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Colobaea nigroaristata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been found only in 
<collectingCountry box="[710,799,1627,1653]" name="Sweden" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Sweden</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[817,942,1627,1653]" country="Sweden" name="Norrbotten" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Norrbotten</collectingRegion>
Co., Gällivare; 
<collectingRegion box="[1133,1276,1627,1653]" country="Sweden" name="Vasterbotten" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Västerbotten</collectingRegion>
Co., Sorsele) and 
<collectingCountry box="[200,286,1663,1689]" name="Finland" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Finland</collectingCountry>
(Lapland: Inari). It is most closely related to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityYear="1830" box="[806,936,1663,1689]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Colobaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="distincta">
<emphasis box="[806,936,1663,1689]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">C. distincta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but differs from the latter species in having a yellowish anterior margin of the frons, wholly black postpedicel and arista, and wider gena; the male posterior surstylus is heart shaped and lacks the slender posterior process of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityYear="1830" box="[898,1027,1735,1761]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Colobaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="distincta">
<emphasis box="[898,1027,1735,1761]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">C. distincta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Nothing is known about its biology or immature stages.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
